SIMPLE: plait
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plait
<hw>Plait</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>playte</ets>,
OF. <ets>pleit</ets>, L. <ets>plicatum</ets>, <ets>plicitum</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>plicare</ets> to fold, akin to <ets>plectere</ets> to plait. See
<er>Ply</er>, and cf. <er>Plat</er> to weave, <er>Pleat</er>,
<er>Plight</er> fold.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A flat fold; a doubling,
as of cloth; a pleat; <as>as, a box <ex>plait</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>plaits</qex> and foldings of the drapery.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A braid, as of hair or straw; a plat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Polish plait</b></col>. <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>Same as
<er>Plica</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plait</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plait
<hw>Plait</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Plaited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plaiting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fold; to double
in narrow folds; to pleat; <as>as, to <ex>plait</ex> a
ruffle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To interweave the strands or locks of; to braid; to
plat; <as>as, to <ex>plait</ex> hair; to <ex>plait</ex>
rope.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plaited</ent>⟦br⟧
